import { Meta, Controls } from "@storybook/addon-docs/blocks";
import * as WithFigureCaptionStories from "./with-figure-caption.stories";

<Meta of={WithFigureCaptionStories} title="withFigureCaption" />

# withFigureCaption

The `withFigureCaption` HOC wraps a component in a semantic `<figure>` with a `<figcaption>` when `caption` is a non-empty string after trimming. If `caption` is omitted, empty, or only whitespace, the wrapped component renders as usual with no figure wrapper.

The design-system `Image` component applies this HOC so consumers can pass `caption` on `Image`; use `withFigureCaption` when you want the same behavior around other media or content.

## Usage

```tsx
import { withFigureCaption } from "chop-logic-components";

type Props = { src: string; alt: string };

const Photo: React.FC<Props> = ({ src, alt }) => <img src={src} alt={alt} />;

const PhotoWithOptionalCaption = withFigureCaption(Photo);

const Example = () => (
  <>
    <PhotoWithOptionalCaption src="/a.jpg" alt="Product" />
    <PhotoWithOptionalCaption src="/b.jpg" alt="Diagram" caption="Figure 1: System overview" />
  </>
);
```

## Best practices

1. _Semantics_: Use for real figures (images, diagrams, quoted excerpts) where a caption describes the content; avoid purely decorative wrappers.
2. _Whitespace_: Empty or whitespace-only captions intentionally skip the figure shell—validate user input if you need stricter rules.
3. _Accessibility_: Always provide meaningful `alt` on images; the caption complements but does not replace alternative text.

## Props

Controls below apply to the demo wrapper. Your wrapped component receives its own props; the HOC adds optional `caption`.

<Controls />

